05014nam a22009135i 9780231556323DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20222022nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802315563237 a10.7312/croc206102doi  a(DE-B1597)638392  a(OCoLC)1341986173  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aBL51b.C6977 2022 7aPHI0190002bisacsh04a210223/eng202203141 aCrockett, Clayton, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEnergy and Change :bA New Materialist Cosmotheology /cClayton Crockett. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aInsurrections: Critical Studies in Religion, Politics, and Culture00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tINTRODUCTION: NEW MATERIALISM AND ENERGY TRANSFORMATION -- t1. ENERGY AND THE DYNAMICS OF NATURE -- t2. VITAL MATTERS: BIOENERGETICS AND LIFE -- t3. POLITICAL ECONOMY AND POLITICAL ECOLOGY: ENERGY, GENERAL ECONOMY, AND EXCHANGE -- t4. OF SPIRIT IN AMERINDIAN, VODOU, AND CHINESE TRADITIONS -- t5. RADICAL THEOLOGY AND THE NATURE OF GOD -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAs humanity continues to consume planetary resources at an unsustainable rate, we require not only new and renewable forms of energy but also new ways of understanding energy itself. Clayton Crockett offers an innovative philosophy of energy that cuts across a number of leading-edge disciplines. Drawing from contemporary philosophies of New Materialism, non-Western traditions, and the sciences, he develops a comprehensive vision of energy as a material process spanning physics, biology, politics, ecology, and religion.Crockett argues that change is foundational to material reality, which is ceaselessly self-organizing. We can observe energy’s effects in the operations of natural selection as well as those at work in human societies. Matter and energy are not an oppositional binary; rather, they are expressions of how change functions in the universe. Ultimately, Crockett argues, we can conceive of God neither as a deity nor as a being but as the principle of change.Informed by cutting-edge theoretical discourses in thermodynamics, science studies, energy humanities, systems theory, continental philosophy, and radical theology, Energy and Change draws on theorists such as Gilles Deleuze, Catherine Malabou, Slavoj Žižek, Karen Barad, Bruno Latour, and Kojin Karatani as well as ideas about spirituality, society, and nature from Amerindian, Vodou, and Neo-Confucian traditions. A foundational work in New Materialist philosophy of religion, this book offers compelling new insights into the structure of the cosmos and our place in it.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aChange. 0aMaterialism. 0aReligionxPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh  aAnthropocene.  aBruno Latour.  aCatherine Malabou.  aGilles Deleuze.  aIndigenous thought.  aKaren Barad.  aKojin Karatani.  aNew Materialism.  aSlavoj Žižek.  achange.  acontinental philosophy.  acritical theory.  aecology.  aenergy humanities.  aenergy.  aradical theology.  areligion.  ascience and technology studies.  asustainability.  asystems theory.  athermodynamics.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311074966340uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/croc2061040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231556323423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231556323/original  a978-3-11-074966-3  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ES